  <md:content-id>m57537</md:content-id>
  <md:title>Properties of Discrete-Time Convolution</md:title>
  <md:abstract/>
  <md:uuid>b94f5937-47f0-442a-9869-7ea77d0e6a68</md:uuid>
</metadata>

<content>
    <para id="delete_me">Recall the definition of discrete-time convolution. For infinite-length signals we have: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mspace width="1em"/><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] ~=~ x[n]*h[n] ~=~ \sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty} \: h[n-m] \, x[m] , \quad -\infty\lt n\lt\infty</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
    <para id="idm503715028128">The formula for finite-length (with length <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi>N</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">N</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>) signals is:</para>
    <para id="idm503715026384"><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>⊛</m:mo><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>N</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mi>N</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mspace width="1em"/><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mo>≤</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>≤</m:mo><m:mi>N</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] ~=~ x[n] \circledast h[n] ~=~ \sum_{m=0}^{N-1} \: h[(n-m)_N] \, x[m] , \quad 0\leq n\leq N-1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
    <para id="eip-548">As with other mathematical operations, convolution has several important properties which we will now explore. We will express these properties in terms of infinite-length convolution; unless otherwise noted, they apply also to finite-time convolution. </para>
    <section id="idm503714999888">
      <title>Convolution is Commutative</title>
      <para id="idm503714999376">Like addition and multiplication, the operation of convolution is commutative. For two signals <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]\ast h[n]=h[n]\ast x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. This means that when convolution is calculated by hand, either of the two signals can be the one chosen to "flip and shift." It also means that the output of a system with impulse response <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and input <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is the same as a system with impulse response <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and input <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. In block diagram form, these two diagrams are equivalent:
</para>
      <figure id="commusys"><media id="commusys-plot" alt="Image">
          <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/commut.png"/>
        </media>
        
      <caption>The commutativity property of convolution, as displayed in block diagram form.</caption></figure><para id="idm503714966816">
Though the output remains the same, appreciating the commutativity of convolution may give added insight to the convolution process. </para>
      <para xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="eip-389">Proving the commutativity of convolution is straightforward; simply apply a change of variable to the convolution sum equation:
<m:math><m:semantics><m:mtable columnalign="right left right left right left right left right left right left" rowspacing="3pt" columnspacing="0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle="true"><m:mtr><m:mtd><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mtext>Let </m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">→</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr></m:mtable><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\begin{align*}
y[n] &amp;= x[n] * h[n]\\
&amp;=\sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty} \: h[n-m] \, x[m]\\
&amp;\textrm{Let }v=n-m\rightarrow m = n-v\\
&amp;=\sum_{n-v=-\infty}^{n-v=\infty} \: h[v] \, x[n-v]\\
&amp;=\sum_{v=\infty+n}^{v=-\infty+n} \: h[v] \, x[n-v]\\
&amp;=\sum_{v=-\infty}^{v=\infty} \: h[v] \, x[n-v]\\
&amp;=\sum_{v=-\infty}^{v=\infty} \: x[n-v]\, h[v]  \\
&amp;=h[n]\ast x[n]
\end{align*}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para></section>
    <section id="idm503714875456">
      <title>Convolution is Associative: Cascade of LTI Systems</title>
      <para id="idm503714874944">Suppose a signal is processed by one LTI system, and the output is fed into another LTI system:
</para>
      <figure id="cascsys1"><media id="cascsys1-plot" alt="Image">
          <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/cascade.png"/>
        </media>
        
      <caption>A "cascade" of LTI systems.</caption></figure><para xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="idm503714871856">Can these two "cascaded" systems be simplified so that they are represented by a single system? It turns out that they can, because convolution is not only commutative, it is also associative:
<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">(x\ast h_1)\ast h_2=x(\ast h_1\ast h_2)</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.
Therefore if a signal <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is input into a system with impulse response <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h_1[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and the output of that system is then the input a system with impulse response <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h_2[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, the final output <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is equivalent to that if <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> had been input into a signal system with an impulse response of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h_1\ast h_2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>:
</para><figure id="cascsys"><media id="cascsys-plot" alt="Image">
          <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/cascadeequiv.png"/>
        </media>
        
      <caption>A cascade of two LTI systems is equivalent to a single LTI system with an impulse response that is the convolution of the cascaded systems' impulse responses.</caption></figure><para id="idm503714835888">
Proving the associativity of convolution is a matter of careful rearrangement of the sums:
<m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mtable columnalign="right left right left right left right left right left right left" rowspacing="3pt" columnspacing="0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle="true"><m:mtr><m:mtd><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:munderover><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:munderover><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:munderover><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>∗</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mtd></m:mtr></m:mtable><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\begin{align*}
(x * h_1)*h_2[n]&amp;=\sum_{m=-\infty}^\infty h_2[n-m]\left(\sum_{l=-\infty}^\infty h_1[m-l]x[l]\right)\\
&amp;=\sum_{l=-\infty}^\infty\sum_{m=-\infty}^\infty h_2[n-m] h_1[m-l]x[l]\\
&amp;=\sum_{l=-\infty}^\infty\left(\sum_{m=-\infty}^\infty h_2[n-m] h_1[m-l]\right)x[l]\\
&amp;=\sum_{l=-\infty}^\infty\left(h_1\ast h_2\right)[n-l]x[l]\\
&amp;= x * (h_1*h_2)[n]\\
\end{align*}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
